    "name": "Alfred Scholz",
    "profile": "Alfred Scholz was a prolific producer of budget recordings, who fraudulently sold recordings credited with non-existing artists and orchestras. Sometimes the names of real people were given credit for performances which were not theirs. Working as a conductor, he performed under the guise of [a730308] as well as many other names. \r\n\"Alberto Lizzio\" was a pseudonym used by Scholz and attached to older recordings which he obtained and then credited to non-existing artists like [a6141413] (who was a real conductor and also Scholz's teacher, but was never on any of Scholz's recording) or himself. \"[a1027209]\" (the name of a real conductor and also Scholz's fellow student) was another name fraudulently used on Alfred Scholz's records, as are [a730311] and [a1130293]. But the works are conducted by Milan Horvat, Carl Melles or Scholz himself according to a book by Berky, John F. (12 March 2003) [revised 2009, 2014]. \"Pseudonyms: Alfred Scholz and the South German Philharmonic\".\r\nIt is not cl",
